Ah, starting a new process with file descriptors connected to its input and output in C++ is like giving a cat a fish and watching it play with it for a bit before deciding to eat it. It's a bit tricky, but it's a fun challenge!

Here's a playful way to do it using Unix pipes in C++:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <cstdio>
#include <cstdlib>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/wait.h>

int main() {
    // Create a pipe for communication
    int pipefd[2];
    if (pipe(pipefd) == -1) {
        perror("Pipe failed");
        return 1;
    }

    // Fork a child process
    pid_t pid = fork();
    if (pid < 0) {
        perror("Fork failed");
        close(pipefd[0]);
        close(pipefd[1]);
        return 1;
    } else if (pid == 0) { // Child process
        // Close the write end of the pipe
        close(pipefd[1]);

        // Duplicate the pipe file descriptor to stdin and stdout
        dup2(pipefd[0], STDIN_FILENO);
        dup2(pipefd[0], STDOUT_FILENO);

        // Close the original stdin and stdout
        close(pipefd[0]);

        // Execute the command (e.g., a shell or a simple command)
        execlp("/bin/sh", "sh", NULL);

        perror("Exec failed");
        _exit(1);
    } else { // Parent process
        // Close the read end of the pipe
        close(pipefd[0]);

        // Write some data to the pipe
        write(pipefd[1], "Hello from parent!\n", 19);

        // Close the write end of the pipe
        close(pipefd[1]);

        // Wait for the child process to finish
        wait(NULL);

        return 0;
    }
}
```

In this code, we're giving the cat (the child process) a fish (the pipe) to play with. The child process reads from stdin and writes to stdout, and we connect these to the pipe. The parent process writes a message to the pipe, which the child reads and processes. It's a fun way to see how processes can communicate through file descriptors!
